1

00:00:01,860  -->  00:00:06,044
In this lesson, you'll be learning about confidence intervals.

2

00:00:06,044  -->  00:00:10,589
When we try to estimate a population parameter based on a sample statistic,

3

00:00:10,589  -->  00:00:12,615
this is like fishing with a fishing pole.

4

00:00:12,615  -->  00:00:14,884
And there's nothing wrong with fishing this way.

5

00:00:14,884  -->  00:00:16,789
It's a perfectly good way to fish.

6

00:00:16,789  -->  00:00:22,644
However, you'd be much more likely to catch a fish if you cast an entire net.

7

00:00:22,644  -->  00:00:25,489
How much more likely are you that you'll catch a fish?

8

00:00:25,489  -->  00:00:28,219
Well, that depends on the size of the net.

9

00:00:28,219  -->  00:00:33,469
The larger the net, the more confident you can be that you'll actually capture a fish.

10

00:00:33,469  -->  00:00:37,935
This net is much more likely to catch a fish than the smaller net.

11

00:00:37,935  -->  00:00:41,655
Though this example isn't exactly the same as building a confidence interval,

12

00:00:41,655  -->  00:00:43,500
because we consider a parameter to be

13

00:00:43,500  -->  00:00:47,155
a non-moving number and not a moving fish amongst water.

14

00:00:47,155  -->  00:00:52,170
This idea that providing an interval and not just a single estimate will help us

15

00:00:52,170  -->  00:00:54,060
gain confidence in our ability to capture

16

00:00:54,060  -->  00:00:57,750
a population parameter is at the core of confidence intervals.

17

00:00:57,750  -->  00:00:59,460
And the wider our interval,

18

00:00:59,460  -->  00:01:03,450
the more confident we can be that we capture our parameter of interest.

19

00:01:03,450  -->  00:01:05,010
Let's take a closer look.
